{0 day11-layer}

Generic, domain-agnostic primitives for input-addressed build layers
stored on disk. A layer is a directory containing an [fs/] tree (the
filesystem delta, i.e. the overlayfs upper) plus metadata files. The
library knows about layer directories, generic JSON metadata, file
scanning, hardlink merging, and overlay-mount planning — and nothing
about opam, packages, or doc generation. Domain-flavoured layers live
in the sister library {!page-opam_layer}.

{1 Naming: input-addressed, not content-addressed}

Each layer is named by the first 12 hex characters of its {e layer
hash} — an MD5 ({!Stdlib.Digest}) of the build {b inputs} (base image,
package name, and dependency layer hashes), {b not} a digest of the
produced [fs/] bytes. This is a Nix-style derivation key: identical
recipes collide and reuse the cache, even before either build has
produced a file. {!Day11_layer.Hash} computes these keys and
{!Day11_layer.Dir} owns the naming convention that places each layer at
its first-12-hex-character hash prefix under the [os_dir] (there is no
[build-] prefix — the basename is the bare hash prefix).

The flip side: because the key is the recipe and never the output, a
non-deterministic build silently reuses whichever [fs/] landed in the
cache first. Fine for deterministic builds; a footgun otherwise.

{1 On-disk layout}

Every layer is a self-contained directory under the [os_dir]:

{tree@text[
{hash[:12]}/
  layer.json      generic metadata (Day11_layer.Meta.t)
  layer.log       captured stdout/stderr from the build
  last_used       sentinel file; mtime is the LRU timestamp
  fs/             overlay upper: new/changed files from the build

  build.json      opam-package-build sidecar (Day11_opam_layer.Build_meta)
  doc.json        odoc layer sidecar         (Day11_opam_layer.Doc_meta)
  ...             future domains add their own sidecars

layer_status.jsonl   append-only finalisation log (Day11_layer.Layer_status)

packages/{id}/
  {hash[:12]}     symlink registry (Day11_layer.Symlinks)
]tree}

The {e kind} of a layer is determined by which sidecar files exist in
its directory, not by a field inside [layer.json]. The generic library
never enumerates the possible kinds; each domain library owns its own
sidecar format and filename convention. {b Sidecar files must be valid
JSON} — unenforced here (no part of [day11_layer] reads sidecars) but
relied on by cache-walking tools that pretty-print contents without
linking any domain library.

{1 Modules}

The core type {!Day11_layer.Layer} represents a layer on disk via its
hash and directory path, with helpers for the [fs/] and metadata paths
and existence/status checks; it is re-exported as [Day11_layer.t].
{!Day11_layer.Base} represents the foundational rootfs image at the
bottom of every overlay stack. {!Day11_layer.Meta} serializes the
generic per-layer metadata ([layer.json]) covering exit status, parent
hashes, build uid/gid, timing, and disk usage. {!Day11_layer.Last_used}
maintains a cheap mtime-based sentinel for LRU eviction, split off from
{!Day11_layer.Meta} so a touch doesn't rewrite JSON.

{!Day11_layer.Stack} merges multiple layers' [fs/] trees into one
directory via [sudo cp --archive --link] hardlinked copies (with a
[merge_no_sudo] variant for user-owned layers), and plans overlayfs
lowerdir layouts that fit the kernel's mount-options byte budget.
{!Day11_layer.Symlinks} maintains per-identifier tracking symlinks for
layer discovery, and {!Day11_layer.Scan} enumerates layers and those
symlinks from the on-disk cache. {!Day11_layer.Import} bootstraps a
base layer by exporting a Docker image into the layer's [fs/].

{!Day11_layer.Layer_status} keeps a durable append-only log
([layer_status.jsonl]) of layer finalisation outcomes, last entry per
hash winning. {!Day11_layer.Relocations} scans an [fs/] tree for
non-relocatable absolute paths that would stop a layer being portable
between backends or machines. {!Day11_layer.Snapshot} provides
lightweight before/after filesystem comparison (size, mtime, inode per
file) for the native build backend, diffing a prefix to recover the
list of files a build produced.

{1 Error-handling convention}

- Read, maybe-exists lookup: returns an [option].
- Read that must exist or parse: returns a [result] whose error is an
  [Rresult.R.msg].
- Write / create / mutate: returns a [result] whose error is an
  [Rresult.R.msg].
- Best-effort bookkeeping (LRU touch, status append): returns [unit],
  errors silently ignored — they must never fail a build.

{1 Dependencies}

Depends on {!page-sys} for subprocess and sudo access, and on Eio for
filesystem and process effects (most functions take an
[Eio_unix.Stdenv.base]). Has no opam or package-domain knowledge —
that lives in sidecar files owned by higher libraries.

